				=09
					<div id=3D"mw-content-text" class=3D"mw-body-content"><div class=3D"mw=
-content-ltr mw-parser-output" lang=3D"en" dir=3D"ltr"><div class=3D"shortd=
escription nomobile noexcerpt noprint searchaux" style=3D"display:none">Mea=
sure of the joint variability</div>
<div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">This article=
 is about the degree to which random variables vary similarly. For other us=
es, see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance_(disambiguation=
)" class=3D"mw-disambig" title=3D"Covariance (disambiguation)">Covariance (=
disambiguation)</a>.</div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Covariance_trends.svg" class=3D"mw-file-descr=
iption"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/=
a0/Covariance_trends.svg/250px-Covariance_trends.svg.png" decoding=3D"async=
" width=3D"190" height=3D"570" class=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D=
"512" data-file-height=3D"1536"></a><figcaption>The sign of the covariance =
of two random variables <i>X</i> and <i>Y</i></figcaption></figure>
<p>In <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Probability_theory" title=3D=
"Probability theory">probability theory</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Statistics" title=3D"Statistics">statistics</a>, <b>covarianc=
e</b> is a measure of the joint variability of two <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Random_variable" title=3D"Random variable">random variable=
s</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Covariance#cite_note-1"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span=
>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The sign of the covariance, therefore, shows the tendency in the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_relationship" class=3D"mw-redi=
rect" title=3D"Linear relationship">linear relationship</a> between the var=
iables. If greater values of one variable mainly correspond with greater va=
lues of the other variable, and the same holds for lesser values (that is, =
the variables tend to show similar behavior), the covariance is positive.<s=
up id=3D"cite_ref-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Covariance#cite_note-2"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In the opposite case, when greate=
r values of one variable mainly correspond to lesser values of the other (t=
hat is, the variables tend to show opposite behavior), the covariance is ne=
gative. One feature of covariance is that it has units of measurement and t=
he magnitude of the covariance is affected by said units. This means changi=
ng the units (e.g., from meters to millimeters) changes the covariance valu=
e proportionally, making it difficult to assess the strength of the relatio=
nship from the covariance alone; In some situations, it is desirable to com=
pare the strength of the joint association between different pairs of rando=
m variables that do not necessarily have the same units.<sup id=3D"cite_ref=
-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance=
#cite_note-3"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>3<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> In those situations, we use the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_product-moment_correlation_coefficient" clas=
s=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Pearson product-moment correlation coefficient">=
correlation coefficient</a>, which normalizes the covariance by dividing by=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometric_mean" title=3D"Geom=
etric mean">geometric mean</a> of the total <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Variance" title=3D"Variance">variances</a> (i.e., the product of =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviations" class=3D"=
mw-redirect" title=3D"Standard deviations">standard deviations</a>) for the=
 two random variables to get a result between -1 and 1 and makes the units =
irrelevant.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Covariance#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[<=
/span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>A distinction must be made between (1) the covariance of two random =
variables, which is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_=
population" title=3D"Statistical population">population</a> <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_parameter" title=3D"Statistical param=
eter">parameter</a> that can be seen as a property of the <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joint_probability_distribution" title=3D"Joint prob=
ability distribution">joint probability distribution</a>, and (2) the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sample_(statistics)" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Sample (statistics)">sample</a> covariance, which in addition =
to serving as a descriptor of the sample, also serves as an <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Statistical_estimation" class=3D"mw-redirect" tit=
le=3D"Statistical estimation">estimated</a> value of the population paramet=
er.
</p>
<meta property=3D"mw:PageProp/toc">
