<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Comments">Comments</h2><spa=
n class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCovariance&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D17" title=3D"Edit section: Comments"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The covariance is sometimes called a measure of "linear dependence" betw=
een the two random variables. That does not mean the same thing as in the c=
ontext of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_algebra" title=3D=
"Linear algebra">linear algebra</a> (see <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Linear_dependence" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear dependence"=
>linear dependence</a>). When the covariance is normalized, one obtains the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pearson_correlation_coefficient" =
title=3D"Pearson correlation coefficient">Pearson correlation coefficient</=
a>, which gives the goodness of the fit for the best possible linear functi=
on describing the relation between the variables. In this sense covariance =
is a linear gauge of dependence.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Applications">Applications<=
/h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[=
</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCovariance&a=
mp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D18" title=3D"Edit section: Applications"><sp=
an>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></d=
iv>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_genetics_and_molecular_b=
iology">In genetics and molecular biology</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DCovariance&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D19=
" title=3D"Edit section: In genetics and molecular biology"><span>edit</spa=
n></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Covariance is an important measure in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Biology" title=3D"Biology">biology</a>. Certain sequences of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/DNA" title=3D"DNA">DNA</a> are conserved =
more than others among species, and thus to study secondary and tertiary st=
ructures of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Protein" title=3D"Prot=
ein">proteins</a>, or of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/RNA" titl=
e=3D"RNA">RNA</a> structures, sequences are compared in closely related spe=
cies. If sequence changes are found or no changes at all are found in <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Noncoding_RNA" class=3D"mw-redirect" ti=
tle=3D"Noncoding RNA">noncoding RNA</a> (such as <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/MicroRNA" title=3D"MicroRNA">microRNA</a>), sequences are fo=
und to be necessary for common structural motifs, such as an RNA loop. In g=
enetics, covariance serves a basis for computation of Genetic Relationship =
Matrix (GRM) (aka kinship matrix), enabling inference on population structu=
re from sample with no known close relatives as well as inference on estima=
tion of heritability of complex traits.
</p><p>In the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Evolution"=
 title=3D"Evolution">evolution</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Natural_selection" title=3D"Natural selection">natural selection</a>, =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Price_equation" title=3D"Price=
 equation">price equation</a> describes how a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Genetic_trait" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Genetic trait">ge=
netic trait</a> changes in frequency over time. The equation uses a covaria=
nce between a trait and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fitness_(b=
iology)" title=3D"Fitness (biology)">fitness</a>, to give a mathematical de=
scription of evolution and natural selection. It provides a way to understa=
nd the effects that gene transmission and natural selection have on the pro=
portion of genes within each new generation of a population.<sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-Price1970_15-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Covariance#cite_note-Price1970-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</s=
pan>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Ha=
rman2020_16-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Covariance#cite_note-Harman2020-16"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_financial_economics">In =
financial economics</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DCovariance&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D20" title=3D"Edit sectio=
n: In financial economics"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsecti=
on-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Covariances play a key role in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Financial_economics" title=3D"Financial economics">financial economics</a>,=
 especially in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Modern_portfolio_th=
eory" title=3D"Modern portfolio theory">modern portfolio theory</a> and in =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capital_asset_pricing_model" t=
itle=3D"Capital asset pricing model">capital asset pricing model</a>. Covar=
iances among various assets' returns are used to determine, under certain a=
ssumptions, the relative amounts of different assets that investors should =
(in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Normative_economics" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Normative economics">normative analysis</a>) or a=
re predicted to (in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Positive_eco=
nomics" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Positive economics">positive analysi=
s</a>) choose to hold in a context of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Diversification_(finance)" title=3D"Diversification (finance)">diversif=
ication</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"In_meteorological_and_ocean=
ographic_data_assimilation">In meteorological and oceanographic data assimi=
lation</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bra=
